nd possibly Great and Little Holland (Essex). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’.","English: habitational name either from Hoeland (Farm) in Bury (Sussex), or from Holland's Barn in Albourne (Sussex). The placename in Bury has the same etymology as in 1 above, while the placename in Albourne may derive from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hole, hollow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hollands","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  , especially 3, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Dutch: genitivized form of   Holland  ."]},{"name":"Howland","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  .","Americanized form of Norwegian   Hovland  .","History: Howland was the name of three Quaker brothers, original settlers in Marshfield, MA. They were from Huntingdonshire, England. The eldest, John Howland (<i>c.</i> 1593–1672) was a passenger on the <i>Mayflower</i>, servant to Gov. John Carver, who died in the first winter at Plymouth Colony."]},{"name":"Hollander","meanings":["Dutch (also <b>Den Hollander</b>), German (also <b>Holländer</b>), English, Swedish, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Holland (see   Holland   1)."]},{"name":"Holand","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Holland  .","Norwegian: habitational name from about twenty farmsteads so named, composed of Old Norse <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, field’, denoting a high-lying farm."]},{"name":"Aland","meanings":["Scandinavian (<b>Åland</b>): topographic name from the Åland Islands in the Gulf of Bothnia.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>atte lande</i> (Old French <i>laund</i>) ‘dweller at the glade or pasture’, or sometimes perhaps, ‘dweller at the old cultivated land(s)’ from Old English <i>eald</i>, <i>ald</i> ‘old’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."]},{"name":"Hollon","meanings":["English: altered form of   Holland  ."]}]},{"name":"Angharad","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old Celtic intensive prefix <i>an-</i> + <i>cār</i> ‘love’ + the noun suffix <i>-ad</i>. This was the name of the mother of the 12th-century chronicler  Giraldus Cambrensis  (‘Gerald the Welshman’). In the <i>Mabinogi</i>, Angharad Golden Hand at first rejects Peredur's suit, but later falls in love with him when he comes back as the unknown Mute Knight. The name has been strongly revived in Wales since the 1940s, borne, for example, by the actress  Angharad Rees  (  1949-2012 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Angharad Holland was born about 1370, in Merionethshire, Wales as the daughter of Sander Holland and Alice Pigot. She had at least 1 son with Rhys ap Llywelyn."},"et":{"about 1370–":"umbes 1370–Surnud","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1501–Female":"1501–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1501":"1501","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales","of Garthgarmon,Llanrwst,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1370–":"noin 1370–Kuollut","1370–Female":"1370–Kuollut","1501–Female":"1501–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1370":"noin 1370","about 1390":"noin 1390","1501":"1501","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales","of Garthgarmon,Llanrwst,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1370–":"environ 1370–Décédée","1370–Female":"1370–Décédée","1501–Female":"1501–Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1390–Male":"1390–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","about 1370":"environ 1370","about 1390":"environ 1390","1501":"1501","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Galles","of Garthgarmon,Llanrwst,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Angharad Holland est née environ 1370,